    "summary": "The First Congo War (1996–1997) was a brief but decisive conflict that overthrew the long-standing dictatorship of Mobutu Sese Seko in Zaire and installed Laurent-Désiré Kabila as president of the renamed Democratic Republic of the Congo. The war was primarily driven by Rwanda and Uganda, which backed a rebellion led by Kabila's Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire. Rwanda's immediate motivation was to destroy Hutu extremist camps in eastern Zaire from which génocidaires were attacking Rwanda following the [[event:2695|Rwandan Genocide]].\n\nMobutu's government had been severely weakened by decades of kleptocracy and the withdrawal of Western support after the Cold War. Rebel forces swept across the vast country with remarkable speed, facing little effective military resistance. Mobutu fled into exile in May 1997 and died of cancer in September. The war appeared to promise a new beginning for the long-suffering DRC, but Kabila's government quickly disappointed hopes for democratic reform, and he was overthrown by Rwanda and Uganda the following year, triggering the far more devastating [[event:3387|Second Congo War]].",
